00:41:16.330 --> 00:41:19.690
How has LA fit into your
writing or your storytelling

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:21.520
at all, if it has?

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:26.110
And what do you think the
future, optimistic or otherwise

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:28.522
is, for where we are right now?

00:41:28.522 --> 00:41:31.780
CORY DOCTOROW: Wow, well, so
I had written a bunch of stuff

00:41:31.780 --> 00:41:34.510
that's set in and
around LA, especially

00:41:34.510 --> 00:41:36.340
in the San Fernando Valley.

00:41:36.340 --> 00:41:39.550
I find it really
fascinating around there.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:43.570
It's such a poster child
for different kinds

00:41:43.570 --> 00:41:46.090
of ambitious Americanism--

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:50.170
car culture, Lockheed Martin.

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:53.660
It's where you go to
live the American dream

00:41:53.660 --> 00:41:54.535
and have a big house.

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:00.940
Burbank is this really
weird city in that it's

00:42:00.940 --> 00:42:02.950
like completely run by itself.

00:42:02.950 --> 00:42:05.770
It's not part of the city of
LA, although it's in LA county.

00:42:05.770 --> 00:42:08.350
And it's the spectacularly
well-run city where all

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:10.750
the services are like--

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:14.957
it's like being in like an
episode of "Father Knows Best."

00:42:14.957 --> 00:42:17.290
The fire department is full
of friendly efficient dudes,

00:42:17.290 --> 00:42:19.870
and so is the water and
power department, and so

00:42:19.870 --> 00:42:22.540
are their garbage men,
and are the schools.

00:42:22.540 --> 00:42:24.010
And the houses all
look like b-roll

00:42:24.010 --> 00:42:25.676
from "Father Knows
Best," because that's

00:42:25.676 --> 00:42:29.140
where they shot the b-roll
for "Father Knows Best," so

00:42:29.140 --> 00:42:31.184
thinking about how that
lives in the 21st century

00:42:31.184 --> 00:42:32.350
has been really interesting.

00:42:32.350 --> 00:42:35.560
I just wrote a ton of
stuff for a TV pitch

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:39.130
that a studio put
together with Alex Gibney,

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:42.790
about machine learning
and its future.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.580
And I wrote these fiction
sequences where I set it

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:47.320
all in the San Fernando Valley.

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:49.720
And it was about things like
the future self-driving cars

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:51.850
in a place that's designed
around the automobile

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:53.810
and the future of
work automation

00:42:53.810 --> 00:42:56.500
in a place where all of
the white collar jobs

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:57.970
are super automatable.

00:42:57.970 --> 00:42:59.740
They're things like
insurance adjuster

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:02.350
and a bunch of
low-level health stuff,

00:43:02.350 --> 00:43:03.850
like that we have
these giant health

00:43:03.850 --> 00:43:06.280
centers where 85% of the
stuff that's done there

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:08.530
is super routinized.

00:43:08.530 --> 00:43:10.540
And it's just such
a ground zero for it

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:12.625
and such ground zero
for weird politics,

00:43:12.625 --> 00:43:14.080
where there are these--

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:17.410
although LA, as a city,
a coastal city in the US,

00:43:17.410 --> 00:43:20.130
is pretty blue--

00:43:20.130 --> 00:43:22.540
the San Fernando Valley
is full of some deep red.

00:43:22.540 --> 00:43:24.520
And so you know what
does that look like?

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:26.710
And what does austerity
look like in a city

00:43:26.710 --> 00:43:27.640
that doesn't have it?

00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:30.850
And because it's also a
cheap place and an edge city,

00:43:30.850 --> 00:43:33.410
it's full of people
who have less money.

00:43:33.410 --> 00:43:36.920
So it's much more diverse
than you'd expect, as well.

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:38.560
And then the last
thing that it has,

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:41.260
that I think all of
LA benefits from,

00:43:41.260 --> 00:43:45.040
is the upside of sprawl,
which is that sprawl means

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:48.040
that somewhere
that you can reach,

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:50.260
there is a storefront
that is for rent

00:43:50.260 --> 00:43:54.100
so cheaply, that no idea how
matter how weird or dumb it is,

00:43:54.100 --> 00:43:55.510
can't get a shot.

00:43:55.510 --> 00:43:57.510
Whereas like New
York, it's like there

00:43:57.510 --> 00:44:00.080
are three kinds of businesses
that you can have in New York--

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:04.960
there's a bodega, there is a
CVS, and there's a bank, right?

00:44:04.960 --> 00:44:07.330
And it's like the
recycled backgrounds

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:10.930
of "Flintstones" cartoons
now, walking through midtown--

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:14.350
just the same five stores
over and over and over again.

00:44:14.350 --> 00:44:16.750
Whereas if you've lived
in LA for any time,

00:44:16.750 --> 00:44:19.150
you know that every neighborhood
gets a sushi joint that

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:20.860
would have a Michelin
star in a strip

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:24.760
mall between a vaping store
and a Mail Boxes Et Cetera

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:27.320
that just the locals know about.

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:31.480
And so that is the
plus and minus.

00:44:31.480 --> 00:44:34.300
In terms of the future
of LA, I don't know.

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:37.360
I mean, we're looking to
buy a house in Burbank,

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:41.515
and LA being in the midst
of the same housing bubble

00:44:41.515 --> 00:44:44.140
that all the great cities are in
the middle of, we keep getting

00:44:44.140 --> 00:44:44.640
outbid.

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:47.500
So we're driving around to
a house viewing this summer,

00:44:47.500 --> 00:44:50.740
and my wife, who's
British, says, so

00:44:50.740 --> 00:44:53.950
what's the earthquake
stuff like in Burbank?

00:44:53.950 --> 00:44:56.590
We're like away from the main
part of the earthquakes, right?

00:44:56.590 --> 00:44:58.820
I'm like, well,
let's have a look.

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:00.160
So I Google it.

00:45:00.160 --> 00:45:04.010
We are, like, on the San Andreas
fault. That's in our house,

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:04.510
right?

00:45:04.510 --> 00:45:07.444
And then there's like three
more immediately next to us.

00:45:07.444 --> 00:45:09.610
And you kind of just got
to take them at their word.

00:45:09.610 --> 00:45:12.430
I moved to San Francisco
right after Loma Prieta,

00:45:12.430 --> 00:45:14.200
when all of the
retrofitting was going

00:45:14.200 --> 00:45:15.783
on in the middle of
the dotcom bubble.

00:45:15.783 --> 00:45:19.351
So every dotcom was renting
spectacularly expensive

00:45:19.351 --> 00:45:21.850
real estate in a building that
was a construction zone where

00:45:21.850 --> 00:45:24.040
they were putting
up cantilevered Xs

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:26.624
the entire length of it, that
no one knew whether they'd work.

00:45:26.624 --> 00:45:29.123
And I think we still don't know
whether they'll work, right?

00:45:29.123 --> 00:45:31.480
I think a lot of The Big
One seismic retrofitting

00:45:31.480 --> 00:45:34.210
is based on super
theoretical models.

00:45:34.210 --> 00:45:37.330
And even when we
test those models,

00:45:37.330 --> 00:45:40.120
we make assumptions about
the material properties

00:45:40.120 --> 00:45:43.087
of older buildings that
are really unwarranted.

00:45:43.087 --> 00:45:44.920
We say, well, that's a
wooden building built

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:47.692
with timbers in 1925.

00:45:47.692 --> 00:45:49.400
We know what the
properties of those are.

00:45:49.400 --> 00:45:52.240
But we are assuming a
perfectly spherical cow

00:45:52.240 --> 00:45:55.060
of uniform density on
a frictionless surface.

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:59.530
They did not have uniform
building inspection in 1925.

00:45:59.530 --> 00:46:02.044
They used bubble gum and spit
just like everybody else.

00:46:02.044 --> 00:46:04.210
And so even though we go,
oh, that's been brought up

00:46:04.210 --> 00:46:05.654
to code with seismic
retrofitting,

00:46:05.654 --> 00:46:07.570
the assumptions about
the underlying materials

00:46:07.570 --> 00:46:11.696
and construction
techniques are--

00:46:11.696 --> 00:46:13.570
we all know that they're
totally unwarranted.

00:46:13.570 --> 00:46:15.320
We know that if you
ripped up the drywall,

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:17.950
you'd find studs that were just
not nailed to anything, just

00:46:17.950 --> 00:46:18.700
sitting there.

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:21.470
That someone was like, eh.

00:46:21.470 --> 00:46:23.740
I mean, we've all
been there, right?

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:25.360
So I don't know.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:27.300
I don't know what the
hell's going to happen

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:28.860
when The Big One comes.

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:30.075
It scares the shit out of me.

00:46:30.075 --> 00:46:32.200
And we just had a huge fire
in Burbank where we all

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:35.230
had to stay indoors.

00:46:35.230 --> 00:46:40.660
The one thing I do hope is that
given how collegial Burbank is,

00:46:40.660 --> 00:46:41.410
and it is--

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:43.960
our neighborhood is super
walkable and it's full

00:46:43.960 --> 00:46:45.610
of people who know each other--

00:46:45.610 --> 00:46:49.870
that the resilience is
there in time of crisis.

00:46:49.870 --> 00:46:53.950
Like, Bug Out Bags are
for cowards, right?

00:46:53.950 --> 00:46:57.190
Like, if your first
reaction to the disaster

00:46:57.190 --> 00:46:59.440
is to run for the hills,
the one thing we know

00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:02.470
is that you will not contribute
to the recovery, right?

00:47:02.470 --> 00:47:04.900
If the lights go out and
you run to the hills,

00:47:04.900 --> 00:47:06.640
you will not be a
party to the Turning

00:47:06.640 --> 00:47:08.195
the Lights Back On Project.

00:47:08.195 --> 00:47:09.820
You're going to be
waiting in the hills

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:11.800
while other people
sort your shit out,

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:14.680
and then coming back and
going, hey, what did I miss?

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:20.500
And so Burbank is full of people
who I have kind of weak ties

00:47:20.500 --> 00:47:24.160
with, who I feel like I could
ring their doorbell and say,

00:47:24.160 --> 00:47:28.260
our freezer's knocked out so
we're smoking all the meat.

00:47:28.260 --> 00:47:31.250
Do you want to come
over for a barbecue?

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:33.130
And that's, I
think, the best hope

00:47:33.130 --> 00:47:35.335
we have of surviving a crisis.

